When I heard about that great Haitian Grio place, we decided to give it a try while we were in Miami; it was a big mistake. First of all, when I was finally able to order over the phone( after calling for more than 15 mins), the guy already said with an attitude that I was talking too fast. However, when I asked him to tell me about the menu, this is where I got lost, it looks like I was in a speed reading competion where he definitely wanted to win; indeed he did. When we came to pick up the order after puzzling out where to park and we are talking about common sense folks(parking is horrible by the way), we waited an additional 35 minutes, standing in a hot, small, and kind of smelly place( no chairs or if there was,  maybe two or three; so many people were standing and waiting in such small place... I though I was going to pass out and I am not claustrophobic! And again no apologies for the waiting time; it's okay I guess ... After we finally had the food and went back to our hotel and eat, we were facing some dry fried sad and undercooked plantains; the grio meat was hard with no taste, the rice was not edible at all; the small lettuce salad was dead for days and looked miserable;  the "pickliz" wa certainly not authentic,  it's made of some carrots and onion swimming in an clear orange liquid ... What was that? We were brave enough to taste it...I did not taste any spiciness or seasoning. That's frankly a food crime! We had to throw away all the food; such a big deception... If you are looking for authentic, fresh, or good food, this is definitely not the place to go to.
